After 25 years of political tension, the Surinaamse Revolution of 1980 manifested the country’s return to multiparty democracy under which new and challenging political culture has begun to manifest itself in the public arena. This moral and political principle is one of the most highly fundamental elements of political building. In this way, the political culture of democratic practices in Suriname will progress towards economic development.

After the overthrow of President Venetiaan on August 1, 2010, the fourth Presidential election was held in this country one year later and J.W. Rojo is elected the fifth President of the country. There are currently no political parties operating in the country.

The major challenges and difficulties that are currently faced by each country and state over the world are areas of politics such as unemployment, poverty, crime, social worsening, economic crisis, corruption, environmental problem, the problem of national security, terrorism, beds, limiting the rights of citizens, pressure of religious and ethnic groups, Migration, weakness of the state, poor democratic transformation and political awareness and many other issues.
